# OS Icon

`TxOsIcon` renders a macOS, Windows, or Linux glyph from `platform` / `os` strings. It is useful in release matrices, device lists, and platform-specific settings.

Reviewed against `packages/tuffex/packages/components/src/os-icon/src/TxOsIcon.vue`.

## Basic Usage

### OS Icon
::::TuffDemoWrapper{demo="OsIconOsIconDemo" code-lang="vue"}
---
code: |
  <template>
    <TxOsIcon platform="darwin" os="macOS 15" />
    <TxOsIcon platform="win32" os="Windows 11" />
    <TxOsIcon platform="linux" os="Ubuntu 24.04" />
  </template>
---
::::

## Interaction Contract

- `platform` and `os` are concatenated and lowercased before detection.
- macOS is selected for strings containing `darwin`, `mac`, or `os x`.
- Windows is selected for `windows`, `win32`, or `win64`.
- Linux is selected for `linux`, `ubuntu`, `debian`, `fedora`, or `arch`.
- Unknown values fall back to the macOS glyph. Wrap the icon with visible text when the platform must be explicit.
- The SVGs are `aria-hidden`, so the surrounding label owns the accessible name.

## API

### Props

| Prop | Type | Default | Description |
|------|------|---------|-------------|
| `platform` | `string` | `''` | Runtime/platform identifier such as `darwin`, `win32`, or `linux`. |
| `os` | `string` | `''` | Human-readable OS string used as an additional detection source. |

### Events

`TxOsIcon` does not emit component events.

## Slots

`TxOsIcon` does not expose slots. Pair it with adjacent visible text instead of relying on the decorative SVG for meaning.

## Best Practices

- Always pair `TxOsIcon` with visible platform text in tables or lists.
- Normalize platform identifiers in your data source instead of relying on ambiguous display names.
- Use CSS font-size or text utility classes to size the icon; the component uses `1em`.
- Treat the fallback as a visual default, not a validation signal.

